title: Custom Gene Ranking
text: Custom Gene Ranking workflow designed users already computed gene-level statistics outside SigFun (e.g., differential expression analysis, external tools, custom metrics). Instead computing signature-gene correlations via sigCor(), can directly supply pre-ranked gene list leverage SigFun’s enrichment visualization capabilities. approach useful want : Use existing differential expression results without re-computing associations Incorporate external metrics like effect sizes, z-scores, clinical hazard ratios Rank genes custom statistics (composite scores, domain-specific measures) Compare enrichment results across different ranking strategies using visualization framework

title: Custom Gene Ranking
text: data frame named cor.df metadata(SE)$cor.df least: gene — gene identifier (match ID type rowData(SE) t2g) one numeric column rank (e.g., log2FC, zscore, other_statistics) Orientation matters: SigFun assumes higher values = stronger positive rank. metric inverse, multiply −1 first.

title: Custom Gene Ranking
code: library(SigFun) library(dplyr)  # Load demo data data("expr.data"); data("mapping"); data("SIG_MAT"); data("t2g")  SE_demo <- SummarizedExperiment::SummarizedExperiment(   assays = list(abundance = as.matrix(expr.data)),   rowData = S4Vectors::DataFrame(mapping, row.names = mapping$ensg_id),   colData = S4Vectors::DataFrame(SIG_MAT) )

title: Custom Gene Ranking
code: # Example: simulate custom stats (replace with your results) custom_cordf <- data.frame(   gene = mapping$ensg_id,   log2FC = rnorm(nrow(mapping), mean = 0, sd = 2),   other_statistics = rnorm(nrow(mapping), mean = 1, sd = 4) )  # (Optional) basic cleanup custom_cordf <- custom_cordf %>%   dplyr::filter(!is.na(gene)) %>%   dplyr::distinct(gene, .keep_all = TRUE)  S4Vectors::metadata(SE_demo)$cor.df <- custom_cordf

title: Custom Gene Ranking
code: # Replace with your data # Run SigFun with your metric SE_res <- sig2Fun(   SE_demo,   rankingMethod = "log2FC",   # <-- column name inside cor.df   t2g = t2g,     strings = c("GOBP", "GOMF")      # controls the databases used to plot heatmap )  # Peek results head(S4Vectors::as.data.frame(S4Vectors::metadata(SE_res)$gseaResult)[,      c("ID","Description","NES","pvalue","p.adjust")])

code: # You can use other metrics by replacing other_statistics with your desired metric.  SE_res2 <- sig2Fun(   SE_demo,    rankingMethod = "other_statistics",    t2g = t2g,    strings = c("KEGG", "GOBP") )

title: Data Preparation
text: vignette explains prepare data SigFun. streamlined (sig2Fun()) stepwise (sigCor() + GSEA + plotting) workflows require input format: properly constructed SummarizedExperiment (SE). document adds small checklist, clear column requirements, validation helpers data passes seamlessly either workflow.

title: Data Preparation
text: Expression (assays$abundance): numeric matrix genes × samples; columns rows contain values NA; zeros allowed; preprocessed (e.g., log‑TPM/CPM). RowData (rowData): gene annotations required columns: ensg_id, gene_symbol, gene_biotype. ColData (colData): sample info column names match expression column names. Include ≥1 signature column (numeric binary 0/1). Add covariates needed. Ontology (t2g): data.frame columns gs_name ensembl_gene using gene ID type rowData$ensg_id (Ensembl IDs recommended). (See Ontology Database Setup setup)

title: Data Preparation
text: Provide sample‑level metadata least one signature column. may include multiple signatures (one per column). binary signatures used cor.method = "logit", code 0/1. title: QuickStart with Streamlined Workflow
text: Multi-gene signatures increasingly used precision medicine capture complex biological processes predict patient outcomes. Yet interpreting signature actually represents functional level remains difficult. existing tools designed analyzing ranked genes lists differential expression results, directly evaluating multi-gene signature across transcriptome. result, researchers often fall back arbitrary sample stratification (e.g., high vs. low groups) indirect proxies, can obscure biology driving signature’s predictive power. SigFun developed close gap. Instead forcing users reshape data differential contrasts, SigFun calculates genome-wide associations signature score (numeric binary) every gene transcriptome, ties associations biological functions. package handles continuous signatures (via correlation methods like Spearman, Pearson, Kendall) binary signatures (via logistic regression), adapting statistical model match data type. Critically, flexible, multi-dimensional framework: users can prioritize genes association strength signature, also effect size, variability, clinical relevance, custom metrics - enabling richer, context-specific interpretations signature represents biologically. support exploration across dimensions, SigFun includes 12 integrated visualization functions - heatmaps networks ridge plots trees - operate directly analysis output, making entire pipeline calculation interpretation seamless publication-ready. Built SummarizeExperiment framework, SigFun integrates naturally standard Bioconductor workflows, allowing users move directly upstream processing signature interpretation without data reformatting. Key Features Summary SigFun provides comprehensive framework interpreting multi-gene signatures three core capabilities: Adaptive association modeling: Automatically calculates genome-wide gene-signature associations using appropriate statistical method - correlation-based approaches continuous signatures logistic regression binary classifications. Multi-dimensional gene prioritization: Stores association metrics structured table (cor.df) users can extend custom rankings (e.g., effect sizes, variability measures, clinical hazard ratios), enabling exploration signature function multiple biological perspectives. Integrated visualization ecosystem: Offers 12 specialized plotting functions translate enrichment results publication-ready figures, supporting diverse analytical needs pathway networks distribution comparisons. Standard workflow: Built SummarizedExperiment seamless integration Bioconductor ecosystem. Note: QuickStart vignette also demonstrates streamlined workflow (one-call sig2Fun) can see fastest path inputs interpretable functions.

text: QuickStart (Streamlined) vignette showed one‑call pipeline (sig2Fun()), computes associations, runs enrichment, produces figures automatically. stepwise workflow designed advanced users want full control steps. makes intermediate correlation table (cor.df) explicit, enabling : Inspect association statistics diagnostics enrichment Apply custom ranking add orthogonal metrics (effect size, variance, clinical HR) Try alternative enrichment engines retaining SigFun plotting Reuse single cor.df across multiple ontology collections Tip: use SigFun’s plotting functions, recommend running enrichment clusterProfiler::GSEA(), returns objects compatible SigFun’s visual layers.

what: Build a Ranked Gene Vector & Run GSEA
title: Stepwise Workflow
text: clusterProfiler::GSEA() expects named numeric vector ranked high low. use cor.df$cor Ensembl IDs names; replace metric prefer. Tips Adjust minGSSize, maxGSSize, pvalueCutoff suit dataset size. Users may change parameters accordingly. ranking metric increases negative association, sort accordingly; SigFun’s default cor already oriented decreasing sort.

title: lollipopPlot — lollipopPlot
text: lollipopPlot function generates lollipop-style visualization Gene Set Enrichment Analysis (GSEA) results. horizontal line represents pathway, dot end marks enrichment statistic (e.g., NES GeneRatio). Dot size transparency encode statistical significance, color indicates enrichment direction. connecting line segments can toggled .

title: lollipopPlot — lollipopPlot
code: lollipopPlot(   seDataFgsea,   showCategory = 10,   breaklineN = 30,   x = "NES",   alpha = "p.adjust",   size = "Count",   fontSize = 10,   addSeg = TRUE,   lineSize = 1,   lineType = "solid" )

title: lollipopPlot — lollipopPlot
